      <bioghist id="aspace_3aa06aabb5b06a9c30a315e5234b3f83">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>John Irwin Viney (1882-1942) was born in Liverpool, England and raised in Newport News, Virginia. He received a BA and MA from the University of Virginia and an LS from Harvard in 1905. Viney then lived in China from 1906 to 1911 to work as a student interpreter in Peking and later as deputy consul at Shanghai and Chefoo (now Yantai) during the last years of imperial rule before the 1912 proclamation of the Republic of China. Viney later returned to the United States and pursued a career as a lawyer and circuit court judge in St. Petersburg, Florida.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_ebc4ebb575d8e4ba1a0e8cfbbbefcffc">
         <head>Content Description</head>
         <p>The collection primarily relates to Viney's time in China from 1906-1911 and includes correspondence, financial and legal documents, printed ephemera, manuscripts and typescripts, and a small number of photographs. Of note are correspondence and ephemera relating to several social and fraternal clubs based in China, papers on a diplomatic embezzler whom Viney escorted from China to U.S. prison in 1910, a typescript <title>
               <part>Memorandum on the Political Situation</part>
            </title> by Edward Selby Little, and printed State Department circulars and reports including a <title>
               <part>Memorandum Concerning Chefoo Foreign Settlement</part>
            </title>.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <arrangement id="aspace_334533094a0d8564baadfeba6607864a">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>Material is arranged as received.</p>
      </arrangement>
      <processinfo id="aspace_622020d1c5904f23127269f86bba3ff3">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Eleven nitrate negatives were found among the photographic materials. All negatives were digitized and then discarded following digitization in compliance with Yale University policy.</p>
         <p>Some material originally housed in the folder "Miscellaneous manuscripts, 1909-1911, undated" has been rehoused in separate folders. See the processing information note for "Miscellaneous manuscripts" for more information.</p>
      </processinfo>
